{
  "texts": [
    "Hyperspectral imaging extends this concept, capturing multiple (often hundreds) of contiguous bands, typically in the near infrared (NIR) spectral range, providing detailed mineralogical and compositional information via the analysis of the specific spectral signatures of fossils (e.g., Murphy et al. (2016)).",
    "Infrared imaging is particularly useful in paleontology for uncovering a fossil's chemical composition and identifying compounds undetectable by conventional optical microscopy (Pan et al. 2019).",
    "Although it excels in material detection, its spatial resolution is constrained (Lasch and Naumann 2006).",
    "In context of DL, infrared imaging modalities enriche datasets with chemical information, yet analyzing these spectra may necessitate sophisticated neural network architectures (Signoroni et al. 2019), particularly in the case of 3D spectral data cubes captured by hyperspectral cameras.",
    "Ultraviolet Imaging uses ultraviolet light (typically 100-400 nm) to illuminate a specimen with the image being formed based upon UV absorption and reflection."
  ]
}